{"title_page": "Eric Verdonk", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Eric Verdonk\n| image            = Eric Verdonk 2009.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Verdonk in 2009\n| birth_name       = Eric Franciscus Maria Verdonk\n| birth_date       = 28 May 1959\n| birth_place      = [[Taihape]], New Zealand\n| death_date       = {{death-date and age|3 April 2020|28 May 1959}}\n| death_place      = [[Auckland]], New Zealand\n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| years_active     = \n| spouse           = \n| height           = <!-- {{convert||cm|ftin|abbr=on}} -->\n| weight           = <!-- {{convert||kg|lb|abbr=on}} -->\n| sport            = Rowing\n| club             = \n| medaltemplates   =\n{{MedalCountry | {{NZL}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]] | Single Sculls}} \n{{MedalCompetition| [[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1986 Commonwealth Games|1986 Edinburgh]] | Single Sculls}} \nWorld Championships Tasmania 1990 Bronze Medal\n}}\n\n'''Eric Franciscus Maria Verdonk''' (28 May 1959 \u2013 3 April 2020) was a New Zealand [[Rowing (sport)|rower]] who won a bronze medal at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] in [[Seoul]] in the [[single sculls]]. Verdonk almost repeated his bronze medal effort at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] in [[Barcelona]] finishing a very close fourth. At the [[1986 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Edinburgh]] Verdonk also gained a bronze medal in a race won by rowing legend [[Steve Redgrave]]. His best effort at a [[World Rowing Championships]], in [[1990 World Rowing Championships|1990]] in [[Tasmania]], Australia, was third.<ref>[http://www.olympic.org.nz/Athletes/AthleteProfile.aspx?Print=&ContactID=1371&id=3774 Biography at Official New Zealand Olympic Committee]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nVerdonk began rowing at [[Westlake Boys High School]] in [[Forrest Hill, New Zealand|Forrest Hill]], [[Auckland]], the same school as fellow Olympic Bronze medallist [[Barrie Mabbott]].\nHe also won a bronze medal at the 1990 World Championships in [[Tasmania]] in the Mens Single Sculls.\n\n==Death==\nVerdonk died of cancer on 3 April 2020 in [[Auckland]], at the age of 60.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/other-sports/120802949/rowing-olympic-medallist-eric-verdonk-dies-following-cancer-battle|work=Stuff.co.nz|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020|title=Rowing Olympic medallist Eric Verdonk dies following cancer battle}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1988 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{1992 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verdonk, Eric}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1986 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westlake Boys High School]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in rowing]]\n[[Category:People from Taihape]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in rowing]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New Zealand rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Eric Verdonk\n| image            = Eric Verdonk 2009.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Verdonk in 2009\n| birth_name       = Eric Franciscus Maria Verdonk\n| birth_date       = 28 May 1959\n| birth_place      = [[Taihape]], New Zealand\n| death_date       = {{death-date and age|3 April 2020|28 May 1959}}\n| death_place      = [[Auckland]], New Zealand\n| residence        = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| years_active     = \n| spouse           = \n| height           = <!-- {{convert||cm|ftin|abbr=on}} -->\n| weight           = <!-- {{convert||kg|lb|abbr=on}} -->\n| sport            = Rowing\n| club             = \n| medaltemplates   =\n{{MedalCountry | {{NZL}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition| [[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Seoul]] | Single Sculls}} \n{{MedalCompetition| [[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[1986 Commonwealth Games|1986 Edinburgh]] | Single Sculls}} \nWorld Championships Tasmania 1990 Bronze Medal\n}}\n\n'''Eric Franciscus Maria Verdonk''' (28 May 1959 \u2013 3 April 2020) was a New Zealand [[Rowing (sport)|rower]] who won a bronze medal at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]] in [[Seoul]] in the [[single sculls]]. Verdonk almost repeated his bronze medal effort at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] in [[Barcelona]] finishing a very close fourth. At the [[1986 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Edinburgh]] Verdonk also gained a bronze medal in a race won by rowing legend [[Steve Redgrave]]. His best effort at a [[World Rowing Championships]], in [[1990 World Rowing Championships|1990]] in [[Tasmania]], Australia, was third.<ref>[http://www.olympic.org.nz/Athletes/AthleteProfile.aspx?Print=&ContactID=1371&id=3774 Biography at Official New Zealand Olympic Committee]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nVerdonk began rowing at [[Westlake Boys High School]] in [[Forrest Hill, New Zealand|Forrest Hill]], [[Auckland]], the same school as fellow Olympic Bronze medallist [[Barrie Mabbott]].\nHe also won a bronze medal at the 1990 World Championships in [[Tasmania]] in the Mens Single Sculls\n\n==Death==\nVerdonk died of cancer on 3 April 2020 in [[Auckland]], at the age of 60.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/other-sports/120802949/rowing-olympic-medallist-eric-verdonk-dies-following-cancer-battle|work=Stuff.co.nz|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020|title=Rowing Olympic medallist Eric Verdonk dies following cancer battle}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1988 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n{{1992 New Zealand Olympic team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verdonk, Eric}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1986 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westlake Boys High School]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in rowing]]\n[[Category:People from Taihape]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Rowing Championships medalists for New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in rowing]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ma nam is geoffrey", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Verdonk"}
{"title_page": "1997\u201398 Ukrainian First League", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n  | competition        = [[Ukrainian First League]]\n  | season             = 1997\u201398\n  | winners            = [[SC Mykolaiv]]\n  | promoted           = [[SC Mykolaiv]], [[FC Metalist Kharkiv|Metalist Kharkiv]]\n  | relegated          = [[FC Zorya Luhansk|Zorya Luhansk]], [[FC Hoverla Uzhhorod|Verkhovyna Uzhhorod]], [[FC Avanhard Rovenky|Avanhard Rovenky]], [[FC Khimik Severodonetsk|Khimik Severodonetsk]]\n  | league topscorer   = (22) &ndash; [[Oleh Hrytsay]] {{small|[[FC Dnipro Cherkasy|FC Cherkasy]]}} and [[Hennadiy Skidan]] {{small|[[MFC Mykolaiv|SC Mykolaiv]]}}\n  | biggest home win   = \n  | biggest away win   = \n  | highest scoring    = \n  | matches            = \n  | total goals        = \n  | longest wins       = \n  | longest unbeaten   = \n  | longest losses     = \n  | highest attendance = \n  | lowest attendance  = \n  | average attendance = \n  | prevseason         = [[1996\u201397 Ukrainian First League|1996\u201397]]\n  | nextseason         = [[1998\u201399 Ukrainian First League|1998\u201399]]\n}}\n'''1997\u201398 Ukrainian First League''' was the seventh season of the [[Ukrainian First League]] which was won by [[SC Mykolaiv]]. The season started on July 30, 1997, and finished on July 9, 1998.\n\n==Promotion and relegation==\n===Promoted teams===\nTwo clubs promoted from the [[1996-97 Ukrainian Second League]].\n;Group A\n* [[FC Desna Chernihiv]] &ndash; champion ''(returning after three seasons)\n;Group B\n* [[FC Avanhard Rovenky|FC Avanhard-Industriya Rovenky]] &ndash; champion ''(debut)''\n\n=== Relegated teams ===\nTwo clubs were relegated from the [[1996-97 Ukrainian Premier League|1996-97 Ukrainian Top League]]:\n* [[FC Kremin Kremenchuk]] &ndash; 15th place ''(debut)''\n* [[FC Nyva Vinnytsia]] &ndash; 16th place ''(returning after four seasons)''\n\n===Renamed teams===\n* FC Khimik Zhytomyr changed its name back to '''FC Polissya Zhytomyr'''.\n\n===Teams===\nIn 1997-98 season, the Ukrainian First League consists of the following teams:\n\n{{Location map+|Ukraine|AlternativeMap = Ukraine (1991-2014) location map.svg|width=900|float=none\n|caption=Locations of teams in '''First League'''|places=\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=49.916667 |long=36.316667 |label=[[FC Metalist Kharkiv|Metalist]] }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=50.25     |long=28.666667 |label=[[FC Polissya Zhytomyr|Polissya]]|position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=50.45     |long=30.523333 |label=[[FC Dynamo-2 Kyiv|Dynamo-2]]|position=bottom }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=50.45     |long=30.523333 |label=[[FC CSKA Kyiv|CSKA-2]]|position=top }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=49.066667 |long=33.416667 |label=[[FC Kremin Kremenchuk|Kremin]]|position=right }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=49.85     |long=24.016667 |label=[[FC Lviv (1992)|Lviv]]|position=right }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.083333 |long=39.366667 |label=[[FC Avanhard Rovenky|Avanhard]]|position=bottom }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=51.5      |long=31.3      |label=[[FC Desna Chernihiv|Desna]]|position=top  }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=50.716667 |long=34.95     |label=[[FC Yavir Krasnopilya|Yavir]]|position=bottom }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.566667 |long=39.333333 |label=[[FC Zoria Luhansk|Zoria]]|position=top }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=49.433333 |long=32.066667 |label=[[FC Dnipro Cherkasy|Cherkasy]] |position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=50.75     |long=33.466667 |label=[[FC Naftovyk-Ukrnafta Okhtyrka|Naftovyk]]|position=top}}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.083333 |long=38.066667 |label=[[FC Shakhtar Makiivka|Shakhtar]]|position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.666667 |long=33.116667 |label=[[PFC Olexandria|Polihraftekhnika]]|position=bottom }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.466667 |long=38.8      |label=[[FC Stal Alchevsk|Stal]]|position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.616667 |long=22.3      |label=[[FC Zakarpattia Uzhhorod|Verkhovyna]]|position=right }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=47.566667 |long=34.4      |label=[[FC Elektrometalurh-NZF Nikopol|Metalurh N.]]|position=right }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=50.75     |long=25.335833 |label=[[FC Volyn Lutsk|Volyn]]|position=top }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=46.966667 |long=32.0      |label=[[MFK Mykolaiv|Mykolaiv]]|position=top }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.933333 |long=38.5      |label=[[FC Khimik Severodonetsk|Khimik]]|position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=49.233333 |long=28.483333 |label=[[FC Nyva Vinnytsia|Nyva]]|position=bottom }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.3      |long=25.933333 |label=[[FC Bukovyna Chernivtsi|Bukovyna]]|position=left }}\n}}\n\n==Final standings==\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PR\n\n|team1=MYK|name_MYK=[[MFK Mykolaiv|SC Mykolaiv]]\n|team2=DK2|name_DK2=[[FC Dynamo-2 Kyiv]]\n|team3=MKH|name_MKH=[[FC Metalist Kharkiv]]\n|team4=SAL|name_SAL=[[FC Stal Alchevsk]]\n|team5=VIN|name_VIN=[[FC Nyva Vinnytsia]]\n|team6=PZH|name_PZH=[[FC Polissya Zhytomyr]]\n|team7=CHE|name_CHE=[[FC Dnipro Cherkasy|FC Cherkasy]]\n|team8=NOK|name_NOK=[[FC Naftovyk-Ukrnafta Okhtyrka|FC Naftovyk Okhtyrka]]\n|team9=V1L|name_V1L=[[FC Volyn Lutsk]]\n|team10=SSU|name_SSU=[[FC Spartak Sumy|FC Yavir Krasnopillia]]\n|team11=ENN|name_ENN=[[FC Metalurh Nikopol]]\n|team12=CSK|name_CSK=[[CSCA Kyiv|CSCA-2 Kyiv]]\n|team13=SMA|name_SMA=[[FC Shakhtar Makiivka]]\n|team14=KKR|name_KKR=[[FC Kremin Kremenchuk]]\n|team15=LVI|name_LVI=[[FC Lviv (1992)|FC Lviv]]\n|team16=OLE|name_OLE=[[PFC Oleksandria|FC Polihraftekhnika Oleksandria]]\n|team17=DCH|name_DCH=[[FC Desna Chernihiv]]\n|team18=BCH|name_BCH=[[FC Bukovyna Chernivtsi]]|status_BCH=O\n|team19=ZOR|name_ZOR=[[FC Zorya Luhansk]]\n|team20=ZAK|name_ZAK=[[FC Zakarpattia Uzhhorod|FC Verkhovyna Uzhhorod]]\n|team21=AIR|name_AIR=[[FC Avanhard Rovenky|FC Avanhard-Industria Rovenky]]\n|team22=KSD|name_KSD=[[FC Khimik Severodonetsk]]|status_KSD=D\n|win_MYK=31|draw_MYK=5|loss_MYK=6|gf_MYK=94|ga_MYK=31|status_MYK=C,P\n|win_DK2=28|draw_DK2=9|loss_DK2=5|gf_DK2=90|ga_DK2=31\n|win_MKH=26|draw_MKH=11|loss_MKH=5|gf_MKH=74|ga_MKH=29|status_MKH=P\n|win_SAL=24|draw_SAL=5|loss_SAL=13|gf_SAL=95|ga_SAL=53\n|win_VIN=22|draw_VIN=7|loss_VIN=13|gf_VIN=58|ga_VIN=34\n|win_PZH=21|draw_PZH=5|loss_PZH=16|gf_PZH=58|ga_PZH=64\n|win_CHE=19|draw_CHE=11|loss_CHE=12|gf_CHE=51|ga_CHE=41\n|win_NOK=19|draw_NOK=10|loss_NOK=13|gf_NOK=56|ga_NOK=50\n|win_V1L=19|draw_V1L=8|loss_V1L=15|gf_V1L=56|ga_V1L=45\n|win_SSU=19|draw_SSU=5|loss_SSU=18|gf_SSU=52|ga_SSU=48\n|win_ENN=19|draw_ENN=4|loss_ENN=19|gf_ENN=44|ga_ENN=61\n|win_CSK=18|draw_CSK=5|loss_CSK=19|gf_CSK=56|ga_CSK=44\n|win_SMA=17|draw_SMA=5|loss_SMA=20|gf_SMA=65|ga_SMA=77\n|win_KKR=16|draw_KKR=7|loss_KKR=19|gf_KKR=55|ga_KKR=53\n|win_LVI=16|draw_LVI=6|loss_LVI=20|gf_LVI=65|ga_LVI=54\n|win_OLE=15|draw_OLE=9|loss_OLE=18|gf_OLE=51|ga_OLE=49\n|win_DCH=14|draw_DCH=12|loss_DCH=16|gf_DCH=45|ga_DCH=53\n|win_BCH=14|draw_BCH=11|loss_BCH=17|gf_BCH=36|ga_BCH=50\n|win_ZOR=11|draw_ZOR=6|loss_ZOR=25|gf_ZOR=43|ga_ZOR=84|status_ZOR=R\n|win_ZAK=7|draw_ZAK=11|loss_ZAK=24|gf_ZAK=42|ga_ZAK=79|status_ZAK=R\n|win_AIR=4|draw_AIR=4|loss_AIR=34|gf_AIR=15|ga_AIR=107|status_AIR=R\n|win_KSD=3|draw_KSD=4|loss_KSD=35|gf_KSD=26|ga_KSD=90\n|col_P=green1|text_P=Promoted to [[1998\u201399 Vyshcha Liha|Vyshcha Liha]]\n|result1=P|result3=P\n|col_RP=red2|text_RP=Qualification for [[#Promotion/Relegation play-off|relegation play-off]]\n|result18=RP\n|col_R=red1|text_R=Relegated to [[1998\u201399 Ukrainian Second League|Second League]]\n|result19=R|result20=R|result21=R\n|col_WD=silver|text_WD=withdrew\n|result22=WD\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n==Promotion/Relegation play-off==\nTo the play-off qualified four teams, the 18th placed team of 1997-98 Ukrainian First League and three group winners of [[1997-98 Ukrainian Second League]]:<ref>Valerko, A. ''[https://sportarena.com/football/ukraina-pervaya-liga/yak-i-chomu-gralisya-pislyasezonnya-v-ukrayinskomu/ How and why there were played post season play-offs in the Ukrainian football (\u042f\u043a \u0456 \u0447\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044f \u043f\u0456\u0441\u043b\u044f\u0441\u0435\u0437\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0432 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0456)]''. (Nestor the Chronicle Statistical Club of the Ukrainian Football). Sport Arena. 5 June 2017</ref>\n* [[FC Bukovyna Chernivtsi]]\n* [[FC Podillya Khmelnytskyi]] (Group A)\n* [[FC Krystal Kherson]] (Group B)\n* [[FC Shakhtar-2 Donetsk]] (Group C)\n\nTop three teams qualified for the First League, the fourth and last team qualified for the Second Team. Format was a single round robin in [[Kiev]] and [[Boryspil]], [[Kiev Oblast]]. When tied on points, the main tie-breaker was head-to-head games. The tournament was conducted at almost empty stadiums. The tournament was discontinued right after the second round when it became apparent that Krystal was not able to secure the third and the safe place to receive promotion. The Georgian footballer George Magriani<ref>[http://footballfacts.ru/players/449785-magriani-georgij Magriani profile] at footballfacts.ru</ref> (Podillya) became the top scorer of the tournament with three goals.\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PR\n\n|team1=PKH|name_PKH=[[FC Podillya Khmelnytskyi|Podillya Khmelnytskyi]]\n|team2=BCH|name_BCH=[[FC Bukovyna Chernivtsi|Bukovyna Chernivtsi]]\n|team3=S2D|name_S2D=[[FC Shakhtar-2 Donetsk|Shakhtar-2 Donetsk]]\n|team4=KRY|name_KRY=[[FC Krystal Kherson|Krystal Kherson]]\n|win_PKH=1|draw_PKH=1|loss_PKH=0|gf_PKH=5|ga_PKH=1|status_PKH=C\n|win_BCH=1|draw_BCH=1|loss_BCH=0|gf_BCH=3|ga_BCH=2\n|win_S2D=1|draw_S2D=0|loss_S2D=1|gf_S2D=1|ga_S2D=4\n|win_KRY=0|draw_KRY=0|loss_KRY=2|gf_KRY=1|ga_KRY=3\n|col_P=green1|text_P=Promoted to [[1998-99 Ukrainian First League|First League]]\n|result1=P|result3=P\n|col_RET=green1|text_RET=Retained\n|result2=RET\