4\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0456)]''. (Nestor the Chronicle Statistical Club of the Ukrainian Football). Sport Arena. 5 June 2017</ref>\n* [[FC Bukovyna Chernivtsi]]\n* [[FC Podillya Khmelnytskyi]] (Group A)\n* [[FC Krystal Kherson]] (Group B)\n* [[FC Shakhtar-2 Donetsk]] (Group C)\n\nTop three teams qualified for the First League, the fourth and last team qualified for the Second Team. Format was a single round robin in [[Kiev]] and [[Boryspil]], [[Kiev Oblast]]. When tied on points, the main tie-breaker was head-to-head games. The tournament was conducted at almost empty stadiums. The tournament was discontinued right after the second round when it became apparent that Krystal was not able to secure the third and the safe place to receive promotion. The Georgian footballer George Magriani<ref>[http://footballfacts.ru/players/449785-magriani-georgij Magriani profile] at footballfacts.ru</ref> (Podillya) became the top scorer of the tournament with three goals.\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PR\n\n|team1=PKH|name_PKH=[[FC Podillya Khmelnytskyi|Podillya Khmelnytskyi]]\n|team2=BCH|name_BCH=[[FC Bukovyna Chernivtsi|Bukovyna Chernivtsi]]\n|team3=S2D|name_S2D=[[FC Shakhtar-2 Donetsk|Shakhtar-2 Donetsk]]\n|team4=KRY|name_KRY=[[FC Krystal Kherson|Krystal Kherson]]\n|win_PKH=1|draw_PKH=1|loss_PKH=0|gf_PKH=5|ga_PKH=1|status_PKH=C\n|win_BCH=1|draw_BCH=1|loss_BCH=0|gf_BCH=3|ga_BCH=2\n|win_S2D=1|draw_S2D=0|loss_S2D=1|gf_S2D=1|ga_S2D=4\n|win_KRY=0|draw_KRY=0|loss_KRY=2|gf_KRY=1|ga_KRY=3\n|col_P=green1|text_P=Promoted to [[1998-99 Ukrainian First League|First League]]\n|result1=P|result3=P\n|col_RET=green1|text_RET=Retained\n|result2=RET\n|col_NP=red1|text_NP=No promotion\n|result4=NP\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n===Games===\n{{footballbox\n|date = 6 July 1998\n|team1 = [[FC Shakhtar-2 Donetsk|Shakhtar-2 Donetsk]]\n|score = 0 : 4 \n|report = [http://ffu.org.ua/ukr/tournaments/arch/tprotocol/129800/ Report]\n|team2 = [[FC Podillya Khmelnytskyi|Podillya Khmelnytskyi]]\n|goals1 = \n|goals2 = Tymoshchuk {{goal|28}} <br> Kryvyi {{goal|62}} <br> Magriani {{goal|75||90}}\n|stadium = [[CSK ZSU Stadium]], [[Kiev]]\n|attendance = 100\n|referee = Oleksandr Tyutyun, [[Fastiv]] }}\n{{footballbox\n|date = 6 July 1998\n|team1 = [[FC Krystal Kherson|Krystal Kherson]]\n|score = 1 : 2 \n|report = [http://ffu.org.ua/ukr/tournaments/arch/tprotocol/129801/ Report]\n|team2 = [[FC Bukovyna Chernivtsi|Bukovyna Chernivtsi]]\n|goals1 = Bohomol {{goal|85}}\n|goals2 = Lashuk {{goal|3}} <br> Semotyuk {{goal|49}}\n|stadium = [[Kolos Stadium (Boryspil)|Kolos Stadium]], [[Boryspil]]\n|attendance = 500\n|referee = [[Anatoliy Kutsev]], [[Kiev]] }}\n\n----\n{{footballbox\n|date = 9 July 1998\n|team1 = [[FC Podillya Khmelnytskyi|Podillya Khmelnytskyi]]\n|score = 1 : 1 \n|report = [http://ffu.org.ua/ukr/tournaments/arch/tprotocol/129802/ Report]\n|team2 = [[FC Bukovyna Chernivtsi|Bukovyna Chernivtsi]]\n|goals1 = Magriani {{goal|66|pen.}}\n|goals2 = Belous {{goal|63}}\n|stadium = [[Lobanovskyi Dynamo Stadium|Dynamo Stadium]], [[Kiev]]\n|attendance = 100\n|referee = [[Ihor Yaremchuk]], [[Kiev]] }}\n{{footballbox\n|date = 9 July 1998\n|team1 = [[FC Shakhtar-2 Donetsk|Shakhtar-2 Donetsk]]\n|score = 1 : 0 \n|report = [http://ffu.org.ua/ukr/tournaments/arch/tprotocol/129803/ Report]\n|team2 = [[FC Krystal Kherson|Krystal Kherson]]\n|goals1 = Dranov {{goal|77}}\n|goals2 = \n|stadium = [[CSK ZSU Stadium]], [[Kiev]]\n|attendance = 100\n|referee = [[Serhiy Shebek]], [[Kiev]] }}\n\n==Top scorers==\nStatistics are taken from here.<ref>[http://ukranianfootball.narod.ru/1998/1997_98_p.html Statistics] {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n!Scorer\n!Goals (Pen.)\n!Team\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Oleh Hrytsay]]\n|align=center|22 (1)\n|[[FC Dnipro Cherkasy|FC Cherkasy]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Hennadiy Skidan]]\n|align=center|22 (2)\n|[[MFC Mykolaiv|SC Mykolaiv]]\n|-\n|3\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Vadym Plotnikov]]\n|align=center|21 (1)\n|[[FC Stal Alchevsk|Stal Alchevsk]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|4\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Ruslan Zabranskyi]]\n|align=center|17\n|[[MFC Mykolaiv|SC Mykolaiv]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Borys Finkel]]\n|align=center|17 (2)\n|[[FC Nyva Vinnytsia|Nyva Vinnytsia]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|6\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Rais Tierkulov]]\n|align=center|16 (1)\n|[[FC Shakhtar Makiivka|Shakhtar Makiivka]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Oleksandr Barabash]]\n|align=center|16 (8)\n|[[FC Shakhtar Makiivka|Shakhtar Makiivka]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|8\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Pavlo Parshyn]]\n|align=center|15\n|[[FC Metalurh Nikopol|Metalurh]] / [[FC Polissya Zhytomyr|Polissya]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Vadym Kharchenko]]\n|align=center|15 (8)\n|[[FC Naftovyk Okhtyrka|Naftovyk Okhtyrka]]\n|-\n|10\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Oleksandr Ostashov]]\n|align=center|14\n|[[FC Stal Alchevsk|Stal Alchevsk]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ukrainian Premier League 1997-98]]\n* [[1997\u201398 Ukrainian Second League]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://uafootball.net.ua/1chemp_1997-98.htm 1997\u201398 Ukrainian First League]. Ukrainian Football from Dmitriy Troschiy.\n\n{{Ukrainian First League Seasons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1997-98 Ukrainian First League}}\n[[Category:Ukrainian First League seasons]]\n[[Category:1997\u201398 in Ukrainian association football leagues|2]]\n[[Category:1997\u201398 in European second tier association football leagues|Ukra]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinal standings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997%E2%80%9398_Ukrainian_First_League"}
{"title_page": "Paleontology in Wisconsin", "text_new": "[[image:Map of USA WI.svg|thumb|The location of the [[state of Wisconsin]]]]\n'''Paleontology in Wisconsin''' refers to [[paleontological]] research occurring within or conducted by people from the [[United States|U.S. state]] of [[Wisconsin]]. The state has fossils from the [[Precambrian]], much of the [[Paleozoic]], and the later part of the [[Cenozoic]]. Most of the Paleozoic rocks are marine in origin. Because of the thick blanket of [[Pleistocene]] glacial sediment that covers the rock strata in most of the state, Wisconsin\u2019s [[fossil record]] is relatively sparse. In spite of this, certain Wisconsin paleontological occurrences provide exceptional insights concerning the history and diversity of life on Earth. \n\n\n==Prehistory==\n\n\n===[[Precambrian]]===\nMany [[metamorphic]], [[igneous]] and [[sedimentary]] rock units are exposed in the north-central part of Wisconsin. Although they are mostly barren of fossils, some of the sedimentary ones contain [[stromatolites]].<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\" /><ref name=\"wisconsin-stromatolites\" />\n\n===[[Cambrian]]===\nExposures of Cambrian rock units, many of which are fossiliferous, occur in western and central Wisconsin, especially along the banks of the Mississippi, Saint Croix and Wisconsin Rivers. Most of the rocks are Upper Cambrian; however, others are thought to be Middle Cambrian. Fossils of many groups of organisms have been found including stromatolites, [[conulariids]], [[brachiopods]], [[gastropods]], [[monoplacophora]]ns, [[trilobites]], [[graptolites]], and [[conodont]] elements. Wisconsin\u2019s Cambrian rocks have also produced fossils of more [[aglaspidid]] species (around 12) than those of any other state. A portion of central Wisconsin known as [[Blackberry Hill]] is a [[Konservat-Lagerst\u00e4tte]] famous for its many types of trace fossils, mass strandings of [[jellyfish]], and especially for producing fossils of one of the first animals to emerge from the sea and walk on land (i.e., a species of [[euthycarcinoid]]).<ref name=\"gass-solving\" /><ref name=\"collette-protichnites\" />\n<center>\n{{gallery\n|width=200\n|height=180\n|lines = 7\n|Stranded Cambrian scyphozoans.jpg|Stranded [[scyphozoans]] (jellyfish) at [[Blackberry Hill]].\n|File:Prosaukia.jpg|The Cambrian [[trilobite]] ''Prosaukia'' from Prairie du Sac.\n|File:Climactichnites wilsoni, [[Blackberry Hill]], Wisconsin, Cambrian - Todd Gass.jpg|''[[Climactichnites]] wilsoni'', the trackways from a large, slug-like mollusk at [[Blackberry Hill]]. These examples are about 10 cm wide.\n|File:Protichnites.jpg|The trackway ''[[Protichnites]]'' from [[Blackberry Hill]]. These are believed to be some of the first footprints made on land.\n|File:Mosineia macnaughtoni.jpg|The [[euthycarcinoid]] ''[[Mosineia]] macnaughtoni''---the presumed maker of some of the ''Protichnites'' at [[Blackberry Hill]], and hence one of the first animals to emerge from the sea and walk on land.\n}}\n</center>\n\n===[[Ordovician]]===\nMany fossiliferous Lower to Upper Ordovician rock units are exposed in the southwestern portion of Wisconsin. These include many species of stromatolites, [[fungi]], [[sponges]], conulariids, [[rugose corals]], [[tabulate corals]], [[bryozoans]], brachiopods, gastropods, monoplacophorans, [[bivalves]], [[nautiloids]], trilobites, [[ostracods]], [[crinoids]], graptolites, and conodont elements.<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\" />\n\n<center>\n{{gallery\n|width=200\n|height=180\n|lines = 7\n|File:Isotelus trilobite from Wisconsin.jpg|The Ordovician trilobite ''Isotelus'', found in Wisconsin.\n}}\n</center>\n\n===[[Silurian]]===\nFossiliferous Silurian rocks are exposed in eastern Wisconsin, from the [[Door County, Wisconsin|Door County]] peninsula to the [[Illinois]] border. Fossils include stromatolites, [[stromatoporoid]]s, sponges, conulariids, rugose and tabulate corals, bryozoans, brachiopods, gastropods, monoplacophorans, bivalves, nautiloids, trilobites, ostracods, [[phyllocarid]]s, [[cystoids]], crinoids, graptolites, conodont elements, and jawless fish bones. During the Middle-Late Silurian, the area around modern [[Milwaukee]] contained a massive [[reef]] system. The [[fauna]] that lived there at that time is among the most diverse for its age on the entire continent. Donald G. Mikulic has called it \"a textbook example of ancient reefs.\" <ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" /> Also of much significance is the [[Waukesha Biota]], which is a Konservat-Lagerst\u00e4tte famous for its superbly preserved fossils of strange [[arthropods]], [[worm]]s, and other organisms not previously recorded from Silurian rocks. Among the Waukesha Biota's fossil organisms seldom preserved in other Silurian occurrences are a possible [[scorpion]], [[synziphosurine]]s, a [[cheloniellid]], a [[thylacocephala]]n, [[lobopod]]s, a [[leech]] and other 'worms,' a [[cubozoan]], [[graptolites]], and [[chordates]].<ref name=\"wendruff-paleobiology\" /><ref name=\"mikulic-new\" /><ref name=\"meyer-discovering\" />\n<center>\n{{gallery\n|width=200\n|height=180\n|lines = 7\n|File:Mackenziurus lauriae.jpg|Drawing of the Silurian trilobite ''Mackenziurus lauriae'' Gass, Edgecombe, Ramskold, Mikulic, and Watkins, 1992.\n|File:Meroperyx.jpg| The Silurian styginid trilobite ''Meroperyx'' from the [[Waukesha Biota]].\n|File:Dalmanitid trilobite.jpg| A Silurian dalmanitid trilobite from the [[Waukesha Biota]].\n|File:Probable leech from the Waukesha Biota.jpg|Silurian worm, possibly a leech, from the [[Waukesha Biota]].\n|File:Cheloniellid.jpg|Silurian cheloniellid, from the [[Waukesha Biota]].\n}}\n</center>\n\n===[[Devonian]]===\nFour Devonian formations are located in the southeastern portion of Wisconsin in the vicinity of Milwaukee. While all are fossiliferous to some degree, the youngest is entirely sub-surface, and the others are very limited in exposure and mostly inaccessible, except for occasional glacial erratics found in excavations and along the shore of [[Lake Michigan]]. In spite of its elusiveness, one unit---the [[Milwaukee Formation]]---has been found to have one of the most diverse biotas of its age (late [[Givetian]]) coming from a single formation. Its fossil biota includes around 250 species of agglutinated [[foraminifers]], [[radiolarians]], [[chitinozoans]], conulariids, rugose and tabulate corals, [[tentaculitoids]], bryozoans, [[hederelloids]], brachiopods, [[hyoliths]], gastropods, [[rostroconch]]s, bivalves, nautiloids, actinoceratoids, [[ammonoids]], [[annelid worms]] ([[scolecodonts]]), trilobites, ostracods, phyllocarids, crinoids, [[blastoids]], [[edrioasteroids]], graptolites, conodont elements, fishes ([[placoderms]], [[sharks]], [[acanthodians]], [[sarcopterygians]]), [[terrestrial plant|terrestrial]] [[fungi]], and [[land plants]] ([[cladoxylopsid]]s? and [[lycopods]]). It also includes many types of [[trace fossils]].<ref name=\"gass-fossils\" />\n<center>\n{{gallery\n|width=200\n|height=180\n|lines = 7\n|File:Tylothyris.jpg|The Devonian brachiopod ''Tylothyris'' from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Eldredgeops norwoodensis.jpg|The Devonian trilobite ''Eldredgeops norwoodensis'' (Stumm, 1953) from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Crassiproetus.jpg|The Devonian trilobite ''Crassiproetus'' from Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Melocrinites nodosus spinosus.jpg|''Melocrinites nodosus spinosus'' (Weller, 1898), a spiny, stalked crinoid from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Eastmanosteus pustulosus.jpg|IG plate (lower jaw) from the Devonian placoderm ''Eastmanosteus pustulosus'' (Eastman, 1897) from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Prototaxites milwaukeensis.jpg|''Prototaxites milwaukeensis'' (Penhallow, 1908), a large fungus initially thought to be a marine alga, from the Milwaukee Formation. \n|File:Lycopod axis.jpg|Lycopod axis (branch) from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Cladoxylopsid bark.jpg|Bark (possibly from a cladoxylopsid) initially thought to be a marine alga, from the Milwaukee Formation.\n}}\n</center>\n\n===[[Permian]]-[[Neogene]]===\nRocks of Permian to Neogene age were either not deposited in Wisconsin or were eroded away by the Pleistocene [[glaciers]] and other erosional agents. As a result, [[dinosaurs]] and other organisms of this age did not leave fossils in Wisconsin.<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\" />\n\n===[[Quaternary]]===\nDuring the Quaternary, deposition resumed; however, the local climate was cold and glaciers would come to cover nearly all of the state's land area. Wisconsin contains sediment from all of the Pleistocene glacial stages, especially the stage that bears the state's name. [[Apiaceae|Hemlock]] and [[spruce]] trees formed forests inhabited by creatures like [[giant beavers]], [[horses]], and [[woolly mammoths]]. [[Pinniped|Seals]], [[walruses]], and [[whales]] left behind fossil remains in the state near the [[Great Lakes]].<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\" />\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Increase Lapham.meteor.jpg|thumb|125px|upright|Lapham examining a [[meteorite]] which had fallen in Wisconsin in 1868]]\n[[File:Calymene celebra Raymond, 1916.jpg|thumb|The Silurian trilobite ''Calymene celebra''; Wisconsin's state fossil.]]\nPolymath naturalist [[Increase Allen Lapham]] is regarded as Wisconsin's first [[geologist]].<ref name=\"hayes-increase-2\" /> During the late 1830s Lapham discovered a wide variety of fossils in great abundance in some rocky hills near Milwaukee.<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" /> He wondered about the [[stratigraphic]] relationship between the rocks preserving his fossils and those from [[Paleontology in New York|New York]] described in [[James Hall (paleontologist)|James Hall]]'s recent research. Lapham sent a sizable sampling of the local fossils to Hall in 1846.<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" /><ref name=\"hayes-increase-2\" /> Hall began researching the area and in 1862 recognized the local [[reefs]] for what they were. The Silurian-aged reefs of the Milwaukee area were the first Paleozoic reefs in the world to be described for the scientific literature. They were also the first fossil reefs in North America to be properly recognized as such. Hall set out to formally describe the fossils of the reef, and found them to be among the most diverse of the period on the entire continent.<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" />  Lapham died in 1875 and most of his fossils and mineral specimens were sold to the [[University of Wisconsin]]. Sadly, most of his specimens were destroyed nine years later during a fire that consumed the university's science building.<ref name=\"hayes-increase-2\" /> During the second half of the 19th century the region was prospected by \"gentleman naturalists\" who collected fossils on behalf of Hall and other well known paleontologists. Examples include [[T. A. Greene]] and [[E. E. Teller]] who collected near Milwaukee, [[P. R. Hoy]], who collected near [[Racine, Wisconsin|Racine]], and [[F. H. Day]], who collected in the [[Wauwatosa, Wisconsin|Wauwatosa]] area. In 1877 research by [[T. C. Chamberlin]] uncovered differences in the composition and fossils of the reef-bearing rocks of the Milwaukee area as compared to those that didn't contain reefs. Donald G. Mikulic praised Chamberlin's research on the Milwaukee reefs as \"a classic work of [[paleoecology]] and [[sedimentology]]\".<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" /> In the early 20th century the reefs commanded the research attention of figures like [[W. C. Alden]], [[A. W. Grabau]], and [[R. R. Schrock]]. Gradually scientific interest in the Silurian reefs of Milwaukee waned along with the decline in local quarrying.<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" />\n\nLapham, Greene, Teller, Day, and another gentleman naturalist, [[C. E. Monroe]], also gathered extensive collections from the Devonian Milwaukee Formation. The majority of those fossils came from natural cement quarries that operated between 1876 and 1911 along the Milwaukee River in the area now occupied by Estabrook and Lincoln Parks. Greene and some of the others would pay the quarry workers for their fossil finds, resulting in large numbers of high quality fossils. These beds soon became well known for containing one of the most diverse Devonian fish faunas in the United States. Most of that material as well as that collected after closure of the quarries now resides in museums, such as the Thomas A. Greene Geological Museum, Milwaukee Public Museum, Weis Earth Science Museum, Field Museum of Natural History, National Museum of Natural History (Smithsonian), Museum of Comparative Zoology, and Buffalo Museum of Science. Much of that material has not been studied in depth for over one hundred years, but a preliminary study conducted in 2019 indicates that the Milwaukee Formation contains one of the richest and most diverse biotas in North America coming from a single formation of its age.<ref name=\"gass-fossils\" />\n\nOther significant, more recent developments in Wisconsin paleontology include the discovery of the [[Waukesha Biota]] and [[Blackberry Hill]], as discussed above.\n\nThe Silurian trilobite ''[[Calymene celebra]]'' was designated as Wisconsin's [[state fossil]] in 1985.\n\n==People==\n* [[Roy Chapman Andrews]] was born in [[Beloit, Wisconsin|Beloit]] on January 26, [[1884 in paleontology|1884]].\n* [[Amadeus William Grabau]] was born in [[Cedarburg, Wisconsin|Cedarburg]] on January 9, [[1870 in paleontology|1870]].\n* [[Everett C. Olson]] was born in [[Waupaca, Wisconsin|Waupaca]] on November 6, [[1910 in paleontology|1910]].\n\n==Natural history museums==\n* Cable Natural History Museum, [[Cable, Wisconsin|Cable]]\n* [[Milwaukee Public Museum]], [[Milwaukee]]\n* Thomas A. Greene Geological Museum [https://uwm.edu/geosciences/research/greene-museum/], Milwaukee\n* University of Wisconsin\u2013Stevens Point Museum of Natural History, [https://www.uwsp.edu/cols-ap/museum/Pages/default.aspx] [[Stevens Point, Wisconsin|Stevens Point]]\n*[[UW\u2013Madison Geology Museum]], [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]]\n* Weis Earth Science Museum,[https://uwosh.edu/weis/] [[Menasha]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Paleontology}}\n* [[Paleontology in Illinois]]\n* [[Paleontology in Iowa]]\n* [[Paleontology in Michigan]]\n* [[Paleontology in Minnesota]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|3|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\">Barreto, Springer,  Scotchmoor (2005); \"Paleontology and geology\".</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"wisconsin-stromatolites\">Wisconsin Geological and Natural History Survey (2019).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gass-solving\">Gass (2015).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"collette-protichnites\">Collette, Gass & Hagadorn (2012).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\">Mikulic (2001); \"Abstract\", page 7.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"mikulic-new\">Mikulic, Briggs & Kluessendorf (1985).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"meyer-discovering\">Meyer & Gunderson (1986).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"wendruff-paleobiology\">Wendruff (2018).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gass-fossils\">Gass, Kluessendorf, Mikulic & Brett (2019).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hayes-increase-2\">Hayes (2001); page 2.</ref>\n\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|Paleontology in Wisconsin}}\n* Barreto, Claudia,  Dale Springer, Judy Scotchmoor. July 1, 2005. \"[http://www.paleoportal.org/index.php?globalnav=time_space&sectionnav=state&name=Wisconsin Wisconsin, US].\" [http://www.paleoportal.org/ The Paleontology Portal]. Accessed September 21, 2012.\n*{{cite journal |author1=Collette, Joseph H. |author2=Kenneth C. Gass |author3=James W. Hagadorn  |last-author-amp=yes |year=2012 |title=''Protichnites eremita'' unshelled? Experimental model-based neoichnology and new evidence for a euthycarcinoid affinity for this ichnospecies |journal=Journal of Paleontology |volume=86 |pages=442\u2013454 |doi=10.1666/11-056.1 |issue=3}}\n* Gass, Kenneth C. 2015. ''Solving the Mystery of the First Animals on Land: The Fossils of Blackberry Hill''. Siri Scientific Press., 96 pp. [https://siriscientificpress.co.uk/products/solving-the-mystery-of-the-first-animals-on-land-the-fossils-of-blackberry-hill 9780992997953][https://www.researchgate.net/publication/301567482_Solving_the_Mystery_of_the_First_Animals_on_Land_The_Fossils_of_Blackberry_Hill]\n* Gass, Kenneth C., Kluessendorf, Joanne, Mikulic, Donald G. & Brett, Carlton E. 2019. ''Fossils of the Milwaukee Formation: A Diverse Middle Devonian Biota from Wisconsin, USA''. Siri Scientific Press, 224 pp. [https://siriscientificpress.co.uk/products/fossils-of-the-milwaukee-formation-a-diverse-middle-devonian-biota-from-wisconsin-usa 9780995749672][https://www.researchgate.net/publication/335831201_Fossils_of_the_Milwaukee_Formation_A_Diverse_Middle_Devonian_Biota_from_Wisconsin_USA]\n* {{cite journal |author1=Meyer, Ronald C. |author2=Gunderson, Gerald O. |last-author-amp=yes | year=1986 |title=Discovering a new Silurian soft-bodied fauna Waukesha County, Wisconsin |journal=Rocks and Minerals |volume=61|pages=310-319 |doi=10.1080/00357529.1986.11768462 |issue=6}}\n* Hayes, Paul G. Increase Allen Lapham: Wisconsin's First Geologist. ''Geoscience Wisconsin''. Volume 18. 2001. [http://wgnhs.uwex.edu/pubs/gs18a01/]\n* Mikulic, Donald G. The Reefs that Made Milwaukee Famous. ''Geoscience Wisconsin''. Volume 18. 2001. [https://wgnhs.uwex.edu/pubs/gs18a02/]\n* Mikulic, Donald G., Briggs, Derek E.G. & Kluessendorf, Joanne. New exceptionally preserved biota from the lower Silurian of Wisconsin, U.S.A. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London Series B 311 715-717 (1985). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/253230954_A_New_Exceptionally_Preserved_Biota_from_the_Lower_Silurian_of_Wisconsin_USA]\n* Wendruff, Andrew J. 2016. Paleobiology and Taphonomy of Exceptionally Preserved Organisms from the Brandon Bridge Formation (Silurian), Wisconsin, USA. Ph.D Dissertation, Ohio State University. [https://etd.ohiolink.edu/pg_10?::NO:10:P10_ETD_SUBID:116594]\n* Wisconsin Geological and Natural History Survey. [https://wgnhs.wisc.edu/wisconsin-geology/fossils-of-wisconsin/stromatolite-gallery/stromatolites/]. University of Wisconsin-Madison Division of Extension. Accessed November 15, 2019.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://mrdata.usgs.gov/geology/state/fips-unit.php?state=WI Geologic units in Wisconsin]\n* [http://www.paleoportal.org/index.php?globalnav=time_space&sectionnav=state&name=Wisconsin Paleoportal: Wisconsin] Wisconsin paleontology and geology\n\n{{Paleontology in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Paleontology in the United States by state|Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Natural history of Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Wisconsin| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[image:Map of USA WI.svg|thumb|The location of the [[state of Wisconsin]]]]\n'''Paleontology in Wisconsin''' refers to [[paleontological]] research occurring within or conducted by people from the [[United States|U.S. state]] of [[Wisconsin]]. The state has fossils from the [[Precambrian]], much of the [[Paleozoic]], and the later part of the [[Cenozoic]]. Most of the Paleozoic rocks are marine in origin. Because of the thick blanket of [[Pleistocene]] glacial sediment that covers the rock strata in most of the state, Wisconsin\u2019s [[fossil record]] is relatively sparse. In spite of this, certain Wisconsin paleontological occurrences provide exceptional insights concerning the history and diversity of life on Earth. \n\n\n==Prehistory==\n\n\n===[[Precambrian]]===\nMany [[metamorphic]], [[igneous]] and [[sedimentary]] rock units are exposed in the north-central part of Wisconsin. Although they are mostly barren of fossils, some of the sedimentary ones contain [[stromatolites]].<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\" /><ref name=\"wisconsin-stromatolites\" />\n\n===[[Cambrian]]===\nExposures of Cambrian rock units, many of which are fossiliferous, occur in western and central Wisconsin, especially along the banks of the Mississippi, Saint Croix and Wisconsin Rivers. Most of the rocks are Upper Cambrian; however, others are thought to be Middle Cambrian. Fossils of many groups of organisms have been found including stromatolites, [[conulariids]], [[brachiopods]], [[gastropods]], [[monoplacophora]]ns, [[trilobites]], [[graptolites]], and [[conodont]] elements. Wisconsin\u2019s Cambrian rocks have also produced fossils of more [[aglaspidid]] species (around 12) than those of any other state. A portion of central Wisconsin known as [[Blackberry Hill]] is a [[Konservat-Lagerst\u00e4tte]] famous for its many types of trace fossils, mass strandings of [[jellyfish]], and especially for producing fossils of one of the first animals to emerge from the sea and walk on land (i.e., a species of [[euthycarcinoid]]).<ref name=\"gass-solving\" /><ref name=\"collette-protichnites\" />\n<center>\n{{gallery\n|width=200\n|height=180\n|lines = 7\n|Stranded Cambrian scyphozoans.jpg|Stranded [[scyphozoans]] (jellyfish) at [[Blackberry Hill]].\n|File:Prosaukia.jpg|The Cambrian [[trilobite]] ''Prosaukia'' from Prairie du Sac.\n|File:Climactichnites wilsoni, [[Blackberry Hill]], Wisconsin, Cambrian - Todd Gass.jpg|''[[Climactichnites]] wilsoni'', the trackways from a large, slug-like mollusk at [[Blackberry Hill]]. These examples are about 10 cm wide.\n|File:Protichnites.jpg|The trackway ''[[Protichnites]]'' from [[Blackberry Hill]]. These are believed to be some of the first footprints made on land.\n|File:Mosineia macnaughtoni.jpg|The [[euthycarcinoid]] ''[[Mosineia]] macnaughtoni''---the presumed maker of some of the ''Protichnites'' at [[Blackberry Hill]], and hence one of the first animals to emerge from the sea and walk on land.\n}}\n</center>\n\n===[[Ordovician]]===\nMany fossiliferous Lower to Upper Ordovician rock units are exposed in the southwestern portion of Wisconsin. These include many species of stromatolites, [[fungi]], [[sponges]], conulariids, [[rugose corals]], [[tabulate corals]], [[bryozoans]], brachiopods, gastropods, monoplacophorans, [[bivalves]], [[nautiloids]], trilobites, [[ostracods]], [[crinoids]], graptolites, and conodont elements.<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\" />\n\n<center>\n{{gallery\n|width=200\n|height=180\n|lines = 7\n|File:Isotelus trilobite from Wisconsin.jpg|The Ordovician trilobite ''Isotelus'', found in Wisconsin.\n}}\n</center>\n\n===[[Silurian]]===\nFossiliferous Silurian rocks are exposed in eastern Wisconsin, from the [[Door County, Wisconsin|Door County]] peninsula to the [[Illinois]] border. Fossils include stromatolites, [[stromatoporoid]]s, sponges, conulariids, rugose and tabulate corals, bryozoans, brachiopods, gastropods, monoplacophorans, bivalves, nautiloids, trilobites, ostracods, [[phyllocarid]]s, [[cystoids]], crinoids, graptolites, conodont elements, and jawless fish bones. During the Middle-Late Silurian, the area around modern [[Milwaukee]] contained a massive [[reef]] system. The [[fauna]] that lived there at that time is among the most diverse for its age on the entire continent. Donald G. Mikulic has called it \"a textbook example of ancient reefs.\" <ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" /> Also of much significance is the [[Waukesha Biota]], which is a Konservat-Lagerst\u00e4tte famous for its superbly preserved fossils of strange [[arthropods]], [[worm]]s, and other organisms not previously recorded from Silurian rocks. Among the Waukesha Biota's fossil organisms seldom preserved in other Silurian occurrences are a possible [[scorpion]], [[synziphosurine]]s, a [[cheloniellid]], a [[thylacocephala]]n, [[lobopod]]s, a [[leech]] and other 'worms,' a [[cubozoan]], [[graptolites]], and [[chordates]].<ref name=\"wendruff-paleobiology\" /><ref name=\"mikulic-new\" /><ref name=\"meyer-discovering\" />\n<center>\n{{gallery\n|width=200\n|height=180\n|lines = 7\n|File:Mackenziurus lauriae.jpg|Drawing of the Silurian trilobite ''Mackenziurus lauriae'' Gass, Edgecombe, Ramskold, Mikulic, and Watkins, 1992.\n|File:Scutelluid trilobite.jpg| The Silurian styginid trilobite ''Meroperyx'' from the [[Waukesha Biota]].\n|File:Dalmanitid trilobite.jpg| A Silurian dalmanitid trilobite from the [[Waukesha Biota]].\n|File:Probable leech from the Waukesha Biota.jpg|Silurian worm, possibly a leech, from the [[Waukesha Biota]].\n|File:Cheloniellid.jpg|Silurian cheloniellid, from the [[Waukesha Biota]].\n}}\n</center>\n\n===[[Devonian]]===\nFour Devonian formations are located in the southeastern portion of Wisconsin in the vicinity of Milwaukee. While all are fossiliferous to some degree, the youngest is entirely sub-surface, and the others are very limited in exposure and mostly inaccessible, except for occasional glacial erratics found in excavations and along the shore of [[Lake Michigan]]. In spite of its elusiveness, one unit---the [[Milwaukee Formation]]---has been found to have one of the most diverse biotas of its age (late [[Givetian]]) coming from a single formation. Its fossil biota includes around 250 species of agglutinated [[foraminifers]], [[radiolarians]], [[chitinozoans]], conulariids, rugose and tabulate corals, [[tentaculitoids]], bryozoans, [[hederelloids]], brachiopods, [[hyoliths]], gastropods, [[rostroconch]]s, bivalves, nautiloids, actinoceratoids, [[ammonoids]], [[annelid worms]] ([[scolecodonts]]), trilobites, ostracods, phyllocarids, crinoids, [[blastoids]], [[edrioasteroids]], graptolites, conodont elements, fishes ([[placoderms]], [[sharks]], [[acanthodians]], [[sarcopterygians]]), [[terrestrial plant|terrestrial]] [[fungi]], and [[land plants]] ([[cladoxylopsid]]s? and [[lycopods]]). It also includes many types of [[trace fossils]].<ref name=\"gass-fossils\" />\n<center>\n{{gallery\n|width=200\n|height=180\n|lines = 7\n|File:Tylothyris.jpg|The Devonian brachiopod ''Tylothyris'' from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Eldredgeops norwoodensis.jpg|The Devonian trilobite ''Eldredgeops norwoodensis'' (Stumm, 1953) from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Crassiproetus.jpg|The Devonian trilobite ''Crassiproetus'' from Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Melocrinites nodosus spinosus.jpg|''Melocrinites nodosus spinosus'' (Weller, 1898), a spiny, stalked crinoid from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Eastmanosteus pustulosus.jpg|IG plate (lower jaw) from the Devonian placoderm ''Eastmanosteus pustulosus'' (Eastman, 1897) from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Prototaxites milwaukeensis.jpg|''Prototaxites milwaukeensis'' (Penhallow, 1908), a large fungus initially thought to be a marine alga, from the Milwaukee Formation. \n|File:Lycopod axis.jpg|Lycopod axis (branch) from the Milwaukee Formation.\n|File:Cladoxylopsid bark.jpg|Bark (possibly from a cladoxylopsid) initially thought to be a marine alga, from the Milwaukee Formation.\n}}\n</center>\n\n===[[Permian]]-[[Neogene]]===\nRocks of Permian to Neogene age were either not deposited in Wisconsin or were eroded away by the Pleistocene [[glaciers]] and other erosional agents. As a result, [[dinosaurs]] and other organisms of this age did not leave fossils in Wisconsin.<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\" />\n\n===[[Quaternary]]===\nDuring the Quaternary, deposition resumed; however, the local climate was cold and glaciers would come to cover nearly all of the state's land area. Wisconsin contains sediment from all of the Pleistocene glacial stages, especially the stage that bears the state's name. [[Apiaceae|Hemlock]] and [[spruce]] trees formed forests inhabited by creatures like [[giant beavers]], [[horses]], and [[woolly mammoths]]. [[Pinniped|Seals]], [[walruses]], and [[whales]] left behind fossil remains in the state near the [[Great Lakes]].<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\" />\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Increase Lapham.meteor.jpg|thumb|125px|upright|Lapham examining a [[meteorite]] which had fallen in Wisconsin in 1868]]\n[[File:Calymene celebra Raymond, 1916.jpg|thumb|The Silurian trilobite ''Calymene celebra''; Wisconsin's state fossil.]]\nPolymath naturalist [[Increase Allen Lapham]] is regarded as Wisconsin's first [[geologist]].<ref name=\"hayes-increase-2\" /> During the late 1830s Lapham discovered a wide variety of fossils in great abundance in some rocky hills near Milwaukee.<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" /> He wondered about the [[stratigraphic]] relationship between the rocks preserving his fossils and those from [[Paleontology in New York|New York]] described in [[James Hall (paleontologist)|James Hall]]'s recent research. Lapham sent a sizable sampling of the local fossils to Hall in 1846.<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" /><ref name=\"hayes-increase-2\" /> Hall began researching the area and in 1862 recognized the local [[reefs]] for what they were. The Silurian-aged reefs of the Milwaukee area were the first Paleozoic reefs in the world to be described for the scientific literature. They were also the first fossil reefs in North America to be properly recognized as such. Hall set out to formally describe the fossils of the reef, and found them to be among the most diverse of the period on the entire continent.<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" />  Lapham died in 1875 and most of his fossils and mineral specimens were sold to the [[University of Wisconsin]]. Sadly, most of his specimens were destroyed nine years later during a fire that consumed the university's science building.<ref name=\"hayes-increase-2\" /> During the second half of the 19th century the region was prospected by \"gentleman naturalists\" who collected fossils on behalf of Hall and other well known paleontologists. Examples include [[T. A. Greene]] and [[E. E. Teller]] who collected near Milwaukee, [[P. R. Hoy]], who collected near [[Racine, Wisconsin|Racine]], and [[F. H. Day]], who collected in the [[Wauwatosa, Wisconsin|Wauwatosa]] area. In 1877 research by [[T. C. Chamberlin]] uncovered differences in the composition and fossils of the reef-bearing rocks of the Milwaukee area as compared to those that didn't contain reefs. Donald G. Mikulic praised Chamberlin's research on the Milwaukee reefs as \"a classic work of [[paleoecology]] and [[sedimentology]]\".<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" /> In the early 20th century the reefs commanded the research attention of figures like [[W. C. Alden]], [[A. W. Grabau]], and [[R. R. Schrock]]. Gradually scientific interest in the Silurian reefs of Milwaukee waned along with the decline in local quarrying.<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\" />\n\nLapham, Greene, Teller, Day, and another gentleman naturalist, [[C. E. Monroe]], also gathered extensive collections from the Devonian Milwaukee Formation. The majority of those fossils came from natural cement quarries that operated between 1876 and 1911 along the Milwaukee River in the area now occupied by Estabrook and Lincoln Parks. Greene and some of the others would pay the quarry workers for their fossil finds, resulting in large numbers of high quality fossils. These beds soon became well known for containing one of the most diverse Devonian fish faunas in the United States. Most of that material as well as that collected after closure of the quarries now resides in museums, such as the Thomas A. Greene Geological Museum, Milwaukee Public Museum, Weis Earth Science Museum, Field Museum of Natural History, National Museum of Natural History (Smithsonian), Museum of Comparative Zoology, and Buffalo Museum of Science. Much of that material has not been studied in depth for over one hundred years, but a preliminary study conducted in 2019 indicates that the Milwaukee Formation contains one of the richest and most diverse biotas in North America coming from a single formation of its age.<ref name=\"gass-fossils\" />\n\nOther significant, more recent developments in Wisconsin paleontology include the discovery of the [[Waukesha Biota]] and [[Blackberry Hill]], as discussed above.\n\nThe Silurian trilobite ''[[Calymene celebra]]'' was designated as Wisconsin's [[state fossil]] in 1985.\n\n==People==\n* [[Roy Chapman Andrews]] was born in [[Beloit, Wisconsin|Beloit]] on January 26, [[1884 in paleontology|1884]].\n* [[Amadeus William Grabau]] was born in [[Cedarburg, Wisconsin|Cedarburg]] on January 9, [[1870 in paleontology|1870]].\n* [[Everett C. Olson]] was born in [[Waupaca, Wisconsin|Waupaca]] on November 6, [[1910 in paleontology|1910]].\n\n==Natural history museums==\n* Cable Natural History Museum, [[Cable, Wisconsin|Cable]]\n* [[Milwaukee Public Museum]], [[Milwaukee]]\n* Thomas A. Greene Geological Museum [https://uwm.edu/geosciences/research/greene-museum/], Milwaukee\n* University of Wisconsin\u2013Stevens Point Museum of Natural History, [https://www.uwsp.edu/cols-ap/museum/Pages/default.aspx] [[Stevens Point, Wisconsin|Stevens Point]]\n*[[UW\u2013Madison Geology Museum]], [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]]\n* Weis Earth Science Museum,[https://uwosh.edu/weis/] [[Menasha]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Paleontology}}\n* [[Paleontology in Illinois]]\n* [[Paleontology in Iowa]]\n* [[Paleontology in Michigan]]\n* [[Paleontology in Minnesota]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|3|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"wisconsin-paleoportal-general\">Barreto, Springer,  Scotchmoor (2005); \"Paleontology and geology\".</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"wisconsin-stromatolites\">Wisconsin Geological and Natural History Survey (2019).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gass-solving\">Gass (2015).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"collette-protichnites\">Collette, Gass & Hagadorn (2012).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"reefs-abstract-7\">Mikulic (2001); \"Abstract\", page 7.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"mikulic-new\">Mikulic, Briggs & Kluessendorf (1985).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"meyer-discovering\">Meyer & Gunderson (1986).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"wendruff-paleobiology\">Wendruff (2018).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gass-fossils\">Gass, Kluessendorf, Mikulic & Brett (2019).</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"hayes-increase-2\">Hayes (2001); page 2.</ref>\n\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat|Paleontology in Wisconsin}}\n* Barreto, Claudia,  Dale Springer, Judy Scotchmoor. July 1, 2005. \"[http://www.paleoportal.org/index.php?globalnav=time_space&sectio